  "type": "plotlines",
  "name": "Foolproof Pulp Formula",
  "description": "An outline formula for writing pulp short stories by Nelson Bond",
  "version": "2021.10.15",
  "categories": [
    "action",
    "shortstory"
  ],
  "link": "https://www.storyhack.com/2017/07/17/another-pulp-story-formula/",
  "templateData": {
    "cards": [
      {
        "id": 5,
        "lineId": 1,
        "beatId": 6,
        "bookId": null,
        "positionWithinLine": 0,
        "positionInBeat": 0,
        "title": "Fifth 1,000 Words",
        "description": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "--- Add Your Details Above this Line ---"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Fifth 1,000 Words",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "The fifth section of the story starts with the climax. The entire phase includes the solution, of final explanation, and "
              },
              {
                "text": "denouement",
                "italic": true
              },
              {
                "text": ". It begins with violent action, tears along swiftly, leading to a swift, decisive conclusion – and ends happily. In the detective story, here’s where your cop or shamus explains whodunit, why, and how they figured it out. In the western, science, sport or action story, this is where the Hero fights free and, tying up loose ends, explains to their public how they knew just what to do."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Watch your timing here! Pace your final conflict so that the action of it consumes approximately 500 words or more. "
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Previous action may have been truncated to move the story along – but not this final scene. "
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Your readers have suffered with the Hero for 4,000 words, so give them a blow-by-blow description of the Last Stand, and let their empathies jump with glee as the Villain flinches, cowers, and dies."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Breakdown:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Fifth 1,000 Words ends on page 21 - 25, the final 20% of the story."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "characters": [],
        "places": [],
